\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex107{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The many forms of round-bottomed glass bottles used in chemical labora\-tories require some special kind of sup\-port on which they can be safely placed from time to time when the chemist  does not, for the moment, need them. These supports should not be mad
e of any hard material nor should they be good conductors of heat, as such quali\-ties would result in frequent breakage. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 A French magazine suggests mak\-ing the supports from the large corks of glass jars in which crystal chemicals are usually supplied from the dealers. The manner of making them is clearly shown in the sketch. Each cork is cut as in Fig. 1 and placed on a wir
e ring (Fig. 2) whose ends are twisted to\-gether and the last section of cork is cut through from the inner side to the center and thus fitted over the wire covering the twisted ends, which binds them together. The corks in use are shown in Fig. 3. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex107{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\ab\loch\fs20\lang1033\b 
