\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex107{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 To the owner of a garden in a town where squirrels are protected by law, life in the summer time is a vexation. First the squirrels dig up the sweet corn and two or three replantings are necessary. When the corn is within two or three days of being suitabl
e for cooking, the squirrels come in droves from far and near. They eat all they can and carry away the rest. When the corn is gone cucumbers, cabbages, etc., share the same fate, being partly eaten into. At the risk of being ar\-rested for killing the squi
rrels I have used a small target rifle morning and night, but during my absence the dev\-astation went on steadily. Last year they destroyed my entire corn crop. Traps do no good; can't use poison, too dangerous. But I have solved the difficulty; it's easy.
 }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex107{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Shake cayenne pepper over the va\-rious vegetables which are being ruin, and observe results. }
