\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex108{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi206\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 A careless impetus given to the pendulum may result in a very beau\-tiful harmonogram, but you may try innumerable times to duplicate this chance record without success. No two hamonograms are exactly alike. The harmonograph, while its pendu\-lum swings in a
ccordance with well known natural laws, is exceedingly erratic when it comes to obeying any preconceived calculations of its oper\-ator. In this uncertainty lies the charm. If time hangs heavily or a person is slightly nervous or uneasy, a harmonograph is a
 good prescrip\-tion. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi206\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs24\langfe1033\loch\fs24\lang1033{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex108 The prime essential in a well}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\charscalex105\b  }{\charscalex108 work\-ing harmon\-ograph is a properly constructed universal joint. Where such a joint is made with pivots for its bearings, one pair of pivots are very liable to have more friction than the other, }w{\charscalex113 hich re\-}{\charscalex108 tards the }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\tx1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs24\langfe1033\loch\fs24\lang1033{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20 \tab {\charscalex108 movement and causes the harmonograph to un\-dergo a continuous change of axis. To obviate this difficulty, the joint should be made similar to those used on scales. The general appearance of such a joint is shown in the first illustration, Fig. 1. Stirrups
 A and B are made of 7/8} {\charscalex108 by 1/4-in. metal. Holes are drilled in each end of these stirrups and filed out as shown at C. The two holes shown in the center of the stirrup A are drilled to fasten the apparatus to the ceiling. Two corresponding holes are drill
ed in B to fasten the long pendulum F to the joint. The cross of the joint D has the ends shaped as shown at E. The rounded shoulder on E is to prevent the cross from becoming displaced by a jar or accident. The ends of the cross are inserted through the h
oles C of the stirrups, then slipped back so the knife edges engage in the V-shaped holes of the stirrups. The cross must be so made that the knife edges will be in the same plane. This can be de\-termined by placing two of the knife edges on the jaws of a 
vise and then}{\charscalex129  }{\charscalex108 laying two rules across the other two}{\charscalex153  }{\charscalex108 edges. The rules should just touch the jaws of the vise and the two knife edges of the cross. This makes a uni\-versal joint almost free from friction and, what is most important, prevents the pendulum fro
m twisting on its own axis. }}
