 and in the center of the lower pane of glass paste by the four corners a sheet of tissue paper that is perfectly smooth and quite thick, as shown in the sketch at }}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20B. {\charscalex106 Darken the rest of the window, shutting out all light from above and the sides. Place a c
hair so that after being seated the head of the subject will come be\-fore the center of the tissue paper, and as near to it as possible, and when looking straight before him his face will be in clear profile to the camera. }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex106{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi220\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Draw the shades of all other windows in the room. Focus the camera carefully, getting a sharp outline of the profile on the screen. Do not stop down the lens, as this makes long exposure nec\-essary, and the subject may move. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex106{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi225\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Correct exposure de\-pends, of course, on the lens, light and the plate. But remember that a black and white negative is wanted with as little detail in the features as possible. The best plate to use is a very slow one, or what is called a process plate. }
