I invented the following trick and called it "Skidoo" and "Skidee," which created much merri}{\charscalex113 ment. }{\charscalex108 Unless }{\charscalex113 the trick is thoroughly understood, for some it }{\charscalex119 will }{\charscalex113 turn one way, for others the oppo}{\charscalex115 site way, while for others it will not revolve at all. }{\charscalex113 One person
 whom I now recall became red in the }{\charscalex115 face by shouting skidoo and skidee at it, but the thing would not move at all, and he finally, from vexation, threw the trick into the fire and a new }{\charscalex113 one had to be made. Very few can make it}{\charscalex184\f4  }{\charscalex113 turn }{\charscalex115 both ways at will, and 
therein is the trick. }}
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex115 Take a piece of hardwood 3/8}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20-{\charscalex115 in. square and about 9 }{\charscalex119 in. }{\charscalex115 long. On one of the edges cut a series of}{\i  }{\charscalex115 notches as indicated in Fig }{\charscalex126 1. }{\charscalex115 Then slightly taper the end marked B until it is nicely rounded as shown in Fig. 2. Next make an arm of a two-arm windmill such
 as boys make. Make a hole through the center of this one arm. Enlarge the hole slightly, enough to allow a common pin to hold the arm to the end B and not interfere with the revolving arm. Two or three of these arms may have to be made before one is secur
ed that is of the exact proportions to catch the vibrations right. }}
