\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex105{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 This toy interested me so much that I have made an investigation into the causes of its action, and I think the re\-sults may be of interest. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex105{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 To operate, one end of the notched stick is held firmly in the left hand, while with the right hand a nail or match stick is rubbed along the notched edge, at the same time pressing with the thumb or finger of the moving hand against the oblique face of th
e stick. The direction of rotation depends upon which face is pressed. A square stick with notches on edge is best, but the section may be circular or even irregular in shape. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex105{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The experiments were as follows: }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex105{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 1. A rectangular stick had notches cut on one face. When the pressure was applied upon a face normal to the first, no rotation resulted. If the pres\-sure was upon an edge, rotation was ob\-tained. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 2. Irregular spacing of the notches did not interfere with the action. The depth of the notches was also unimpor\-tant, although it should be suited to the size of the nail for best results. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 3. The hole in the revolving piece must be larger than the pin; if there is a close fit no rotation is obtained. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 4. The center of gravity of the re\-volving piece must lie within the hole. If the hole is not well centered the trick cannot be performed. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 5. If the stick be clamped in a vise no results are obtained; with this excep\-tion: if the stick has enough spring, and the end clamped is far enough away from the notched portion, the rotation may be obtained. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The above experiments led me to the conclusion that the operation of the de\-vice is dependent upon a circular mo\-tion of the pin, and this was confirmed by the following experiments. The ac\-tion is somewhat similar to swinging the toy known as a locust aro
und with a slight circular motion of the hand, It is necessary to show here that a slight }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 circular motion is sufficient to produce the result and, secondly, that such mo\-tion can be produced by the given move\-ments of the hands. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 6. A piece of brass rod was clamped in the chuck of a lathe, and a depres\-sion made in the end slightly eccentric, by means of a center punch. If the end of the pin is inserted in this depression, }
