 of which should be kept moistened with 2 parts tur\-pentine and 1 part sweet oil while drilling. The hole is to be made 3/4}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\charscalex90  }{\charscalex109 in. in diameter. The circle is then marked on each plate and cut with a glass cutter. The plates are trued up, after they are mounte
d, by holding a piece of emery wheel to the edges while they are turning. Water should be applied to the edges while doing the work. }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs24\langfe1033\loch\fs24\lang1033{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex109 The sectors are cut from tinfoil, 1-1/2}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\charscalex85\i  }{\charscalex109 in. wide at one end, 3/4}{\charscalex71\f4  }{\charscalex109 in. at the other, and 4 in. long. A thin coat of shellac varnish is applied to both sides of the plates, and 16 sectors put on one side of each plate, as shown in Fig. 1. The divisions can be
 marked on the oppo\-site side of the plate and a circle drawn as a guide to place the sectors at proper intervals. }}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex109{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The sectors should lie flat on the glass with all parts smoothed out so that they will not be torn from their places as the plates revolve. The shel\-lac should be tacky when the pieces of tinfoil are put in place. }
