a stout board upon which to work up the design. A rivet punch is desir\-able, though not absolutely necessary. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex108{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The material required is a sheet of No. 24 gauge copper or brass of a size equal to that of the proposed holder, plus a 3/8-in. border all around, into which to place the screws that are to be used to hold the metal to the board while pounding it. The desi
gn shown in the picture is 6 by 8 in. at the widest part and has proven a satisfactory holder for a small broom. }
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Carefully work out the design de\-sired on a piece of drawing paper, both outline and decoration, avoiding sharp curves in the outline because they are hard to follow with the shears when cutting the metal. If the design is to be of two-part symmetry, like 
the one shown, draw one part, then fold on a center line and duplicate this by insert\-ing double-surfaced carbon paper and tracing the part already drawn. With this same carbon paper transfer the design to the metal. Fasten the metal to the board firmly, u
sing 1/2-in. screws placed about 1 in. apart in holes pre\-viously punched in the margin with a nail set or nail. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex108{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 To flatten the metal preparatory to fastening it to the board, place a block of wood upon it and pound on this block, never upon the metal directly, }
