\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi201\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs24\langfe1033\loch\fs24\lang1033{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex108 A mortise is cut for the bow at a point 9-1/2 in. from the end of the stock, and one for the trigger }}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs2012 {\charscalex108 in. from the opposite end, which should be slanting a little as shown by the dotted lines. A spring, Fig. 2, is made from a good piece of oak and fasten
ed to the stock with two screws. The trigger, Fig. 3, which is 1/4} {\charscalex108 in. thick, is inserted in the mortise in the position when pulled back, and adjusted so as to raise the spring to the proper height, and then a pin is put through both stock and trigger, ha
ving the latter swing quite freely. When the trigger is pulled, it lifts the spring up, which in turn lifts the cord off the tin notch. }}
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex108 The stick for the bow, Fig. 4, is dressed down from a point 3/4}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\f4  }{\charscalex108 in. on each side of the center line to 1/2}{\f4  }{\charscalex108 in. wide at each end. Notches are cut in the ends for the cord. The bow is not fastened in the stock, it is wrapped with a piece of canvas 1-1/2 in. 
wide on the center line to make a tight fit in the mortise. A stout cord is now tied in the notches cut in the ends of the bow making the cord taut when the wood is straight. }}
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex108 The design of the arrows is shown in Fig. 5 and they are made with the }}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\charscalex109 blades much thinner than the round part. }}
