\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\charscalex106{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs20\langfe1033\loch\fs20\lang1033 {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 distance from each core, the indicator should be parallel to the long dimen\-sion of the face of the case. The case of the instrument may be made in the following way: }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li0\ri0\lin0\rin0\fi196\rtlch\af0\afs20\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af0\afs24\langfe1033\loch\fs24\lang1033{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex106 Secure a piece of 3/8-in. oak, or other hard wood, 3 in. wide and 2 ft. long. Then cut from this board the follow\-ing pieces: two whose dimensions cor\-respond to those of Fig. 5 and are to form the sides of the case; two whose dimensions correspond to thos
e of Fig. 6 and are to form the back and the face of the case; three whose dimen\-sions correspond to those of Figs. }}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\b 7, }{\charscalex106 8, and 9 and are to form the lower and upper end of the case and the finish for the top. }}
\par {\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0\fs20{\charscalex106 Secure a piece of window glass, 4-1/2 in. by 3-1/8}}{\loch\f0\fs20\lang1033\fs20\fs20{\charscalex86  }{\charscalex106 in. that is to be used as the front. Before assembling the case cut on the inner surface of the pieces form\-ing the sides and the lower end, a groove just wide enough to take the glass and 1/16 in. in dept
